name: It Isn't Gonna Be That Way
Silver Threads Among the Gold
comments: As a young man, Rexford wrote poems and stories to support himself while a college student.  Danks contacted Rexford and asked him for some song lyric, agreeing to pay $3.00 for each lyric used.  Rexford provided nine sets of lyrics, including "Silver Threads Among the Gold", which was apparently revised from a poem he had written circa 1866.  Danks ultimately sent Rexford a check for $18.00, implying that he accepted six of the nine sets of lyrics, but provided no specification as to which lyrics he was purchasing.  The song became extremely popular, selling two million copies as sheet music beginning in 1873 and another one million copies, when the song was revived in 1907. They also wrote a companion song, When Silver Threads Are Gold Again .

name: Andantino in D-Flat op. 83, no. 2
comments: This was the most popular composition of organist Edwin Lemare.  In 1921, without Lemare's  permission, lyrics were added to the song by Ben Black and Neil Moret, who made it "Moonlight and Roses".  The piece with the new lyrics was extremely popular, resulting in over one million sheet music sales.  Lemare threatened to sue the lyricists in 1925, resulting in a settlement in which Lemare received royalties for sales of "Moonlight and Roses".  As Lemare had merely been paid a small flat sum for the melody when it had been copyrighted in 1892, he finally made some real money from his work.

name: Break the News to Mother
comments: Written in 1891,  the lyrics were revised in 1897, coinciding with the Spanish-American War, to make the song about a soldier, rather than a fireman.  (Several references incorrectly state that the song was revised after the sinking of the USS Maine in 1898).  Although frequently called a song of the American Civil War, the work actually post-dates that war and is more accurately associated with the Spanish-American War.  The song's popularity was renewed during World War I. We have been unable to ascertain the first released or recorded version of the work due to a lack of available precise data.  Despite the listed release dates, it is possible that any of the versions of this work shown as released in the 1890s could be the first released version.  Recording information about these early releases is even harder to obtain.

name: Guten Abend, gut' Nacht
comments: Johannes Brahms composed this song in July 1868 in Bonn and devoted it to Frau Bertha Faber-Porubszky at the occasion of the birth of her second son. The German lyrics are partially from "Des Knaben Wunderhorn", a collection of German folk poems and songs edited by Achim von Arnim and Clemens Brentano and published in three editions: the first in 1805 followed by two more volumes in 1808. The second verse was written by Georg Scherer, who published this in his 1849 "Sammlung Alte und neue Kinderlieder". The second verse obviously relates to the Christmas period.
